II, III and V have two title pages.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="a">[No. I] Introduction. Containing an impartial account of the prophets of the Cevennes. In a letter to a friend. By Sir Richard Bulkeley. Together with the remarkable vision of Lewis XIV; for the interpretation of which he offered a reward of 20,000 louis d'ors, in the Paris Gazette of November 11, 1689 (London : G. Terry, 1795).--No.II. Containing a most extraordinary prophecy, delivered near one hundred years ago, before the Senate,at Frankfort in Germany, concerning the judgments of God on the whole Roman Empire; the Revolutions of, and the calamities that are to happen in, the different nations of the world, especially those of Germany, France, Poland, Holland, &c., by J. M. Daut (1794).</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="a">[No. III] Prophetical extracts. Containing a very scarce prophetic piece, intitled [sic], A cry from the desart [sic], or, testimonials of the miraculous things lately come to pass in the Cevennes, or Southern parts of France. Verified upon oath, and by other proofs. [by Maximilian Misson] (1794).--No. IV. Prophetical extracts. Relative to the revolution in France, and the decline of the papal power in the world: selected from Fleming, Usher, Jerieu, Goodwin, Gill, Love, Daut, Brown, Knox, Willison, More, Newton, Lacey, Owen, Marion, Cavalier, and many more (1794).--No. V. Prophetical extracts. Relative to the revolution in France...The lives, prophecies, visions, and revelations, of Christopher Kotterus, and Christina Poniatonia, two eminent prophets, in Germany, containing predictions concerning the Pope, the King of France, and the Roman Empire ; with the sudden destruction of the papal power, the miraculous conversion of the Turks, the calling in of the Jews, and the uniting all religions into one universal visible church. Many of which prophecies being desired by the then King of Bohemia, were by the learned Comenius presented to him [by Johann Amos Comenius] (1794).</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="538" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Mode of access: Internet.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="700" ind1="1" ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Bulkeley, Richard,</subfield><subfield code="c">Sir,</subfield><subfield code="d">1644-1710.</subfield><subfield code="t">Impartial account of the prophets of the Cevennes.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="700" ind1="1" ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Comenius, Johann Amos,</subfield><subfield code="d">1592-1670.</subfield><subfield code="t">Lives, prophecies, visions and revelations of Christopher Kotterus and Christina Poniatonia.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="700" ind1="1" ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Daut, Johann Maximillian,</subfield><subfield code="d">1690-1737.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="700" ind1="1" ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Misson, Maximilien,</subfield><subfield code="d">1650?-1722.</subfield><subfield code="t">Cry from the desart.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="970" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="a">BK</subfield><subfield code="b">Book</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="971" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="a">MiU</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="852" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="b">SDR  </subfield><subfield code="c">HVD  </subfield></datafield><datafield tag="974" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="a">hvd.ah6348</subfield></datafield></record></collection>

Finanzministerium über den Zustand der Urproduction, der Gewerbe, des Handels, der Creditverhältnisse und der Verkehrsmittel des Bezirkes in den Jahren 1857-1859 -- [4] Bericht über die schweizerischen Handelsverhältnisse zu den verschiedenen Staaten des Auslandes, erstattet an den eidgenössischen Vorort von der in Angelegenheiten des schweizerischen Handels im Christmonat 1833 einberufenen eidgenössischen Expertenkommission -- [5] Gutachten des Handelsrathes der h. Haupt- und Residenzstädt München, über den französisch-preussischen Handelsvertrag -- [6] Bericht über die Verhandlungen des zweiten deutschen Handelstages, namentlich in Betreff der Zolleinigung mit Osterreich und des Handelsvertrags zwischen dem Zollverein und Frankreich, dem Central-Vorstande des Gewerbe-Vereins für das Herzogthum Nassau erstattet / Theodor Dilthey -- [7] Kleine Beiträge zum Streit über den deutsch-französisch Handelsvertrag -- [8] Sendschreiben an einen Gutsbesitzer über das System der Handels-Balance in der National-Oeconomie, mit besonderer Beziehung auf die Frage : welche Industrie, die der Colonial-Zucker- oder die der Rüben-Zucker-Fabriken aus den Gesichtspunkten des Gemeinwohls, des Staats und des Privat-Interesse den Vorzug verdient / I.C.H. Kupfer -- [9] Mémoire adressé a la Chambre de Commerce par les Frabricans d'Armes de Liége.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="538" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Mode of access: Internet.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="970" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="a">BK</subfield><subfield code="b">Book</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="996" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="c">TSzserv</subfield><subfield code="f">TTL</subfield><subfield code="d">20140901</subfield><subfield code="n">21</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="971" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="a">MiU</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="852" ind1="0" ind2=" "><subfield code="b">SPEC </subfield><subfield code="c">PARS </subfield><subfield code="h">HF 1009 .P18 v.3</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="974" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="a">mdp.39015070869360</subfield></datafield></record></collection>

toc: [1] Journal of researches into the natural history and geology of the countries visited during the voyage of H. M. S. Beagle round the world under the command of Capt. Together with the remarkable vision of Lewis XIV; for the interpretation of which he offered a reward of 20,000 louis d'ors, in the Paris Gazette of November 11, 1689 (London : G. Terry, 1795).--No.II. Containing a most extraordinary prophecy, delivered near one hundred years ago, before the Senate,at Frankfort in Germany, concerning the judgments of God on the whole Roman Empire; the Revolutions of, and the calamities that are to happen in, the different nations of the world, especially those of Germany, France, Poland, Holland, &c., by J. M. Daut (1794).</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="a">[No. III] Prophetical extracts. Containing a very scarce prophetic piece, intitled [sic], A cry from the desart [sic], or, testimonials of the miraculous things lately come to pass in the Cevennes, or Southern parts of France. Verified upon oath, and by other proofs. [by Maximilian Misson] (1794).--No. IV. Prophetical extracts. Relative to the revolution in France, and the decline of the papal power in the world: selected from Fleming, Usher, Jerieu, Goodwin, Gill, Love, Daut, Brown, Knox, Willison, More, Newton, Lacey, Owen, Marion, Cavalier, and many more (1794).--No. V. Prophetical extracts. Relative to the revolution in France...The lives, prophecies, visions, and revelations, of Christopher Kotterus, and Christina Poniatonia, two eminent prophets, in Germany, containing predictions concerning the Pope, the King of France, and the Roman Empire ; with the sudden destruction of the papal power, the miraculous conversion of the Turks, the calling in of the Jews, and the uniting all religions into one universal visible church. Many of which prophecies being desired by the then King of Bohemia, were by the learned Comenius presented to him [by Johann Amos Comenius] (1794).</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="538" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Mode of access: Internet.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="700" ind1="1" ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Bulkeley, Richard,</subfield><subfield code="c">Sir,</subfield><subfield code="d">1644-1710.</subfield><subfield code="t">Impartial account of the prophets of the Cevennes.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="700" ind1="1" ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Comenius, Johann Amos,</subfield><subfield code="d">1592-1670.</subfield><subfield code="t">Lives, prophecies, visions and revelations of Christopher Kotterus and Christina Poniatonia.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="700" ind1="1" ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Daut, Johann Maximillian,</subfield><subfield code="d">1690-1737.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="700" ind1="1" ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Misson, Maximilien,</subfield><subfield code="d">1650?-1722.</subfield><subfield code="t">Cry from the desart.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="970" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="a">BK</subfield><subfield code="b">Book</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="971" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="a">MiU</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="852" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="b">SDR  </subfield><subfield code="c">HVD  </subfield></datafield><datafield tag="974" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="a">hvd.ah6348</subfield></datafield></record></collection>

A voyage to South America. : Describing at large, the Spanish cities, towns, provinces, &c. on that extensive continent. Interspersed throughout with reflexions on whatever is peculiar in the religion and civil policy, in the genius, customs, manners, dress, &c. &c. of the several inhabitants, whether natives, Spaniards, creoles, Indians, mulattoes, or negroes. Together with the natural as well as commercial history of the country. ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Careful copy of an astronomical almanac (natījah / rūznāmah / ephemeris) for the Jalālī year 1235 (indicated as the 778th, see p.2) preceded by horiscope (ṭāliʻ) for the year (given in the corresponding Hijrī / Rūmī value, 1272, see p.1). Presumably observed at Istanbul. Corresponding Hijrī, Rūmī, old Yazdagardī and Coptic calendars dates are given. Contributions to the cataloguing from Elizabeth Kunze.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="546" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Ottoman Turkish.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Title supplied by cataloguer.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Collation: VII (14) ; single septenion ; pagination in pencil, Western numerals, supplied during digitization.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Layout: Written area divided to accommodate tables of 14 columns and 16 rows (with 15 of the rows carrying two lines each corresponding to the days of the month), headed by outlines of square charts divided to 12 (4 central squares and 8 triangles corresponding to the celestial houses) ; prickings for ruling the tables evident in the outer and lower margins.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Script: Mainly naskh and naskh with elements of ruqʻah ; clear Turkish hands ; elegant naskh employed for most headings, some entries and some annotations ; more compact naskh with elements of ruqʻah used for other annotations and some headings ; forms resembling siyakat letterforms used in table entries ; elucidation of symbols employed entered on opening page (p.1) above and alongside the horiscope diagram.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Decoration: Written area and tables throughout defined by gold bands and black lines ; heading of opening horiscope diagram chrysographed "لع يل ١٢٧٢ سال عالم بأفق دار السلطنه العلية العثمانيه" ; many headings and keywords / symbols rubricated.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Support: European laid paper with 9 laid lines per cm. (vertical), chain lines spaced 28 mm. apart (horizontal), and watermarks of lion rampant guardant (see p.2, 8, 28, etc.) and initials "NR" in arms (see p.4, 6, 26, etc.) very similar to Eineder no.1018 dated 1806 but with "NR" rather than "AB" ; creamy buff in color (yellowish hue), crisp and well-burnished to glossy.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Binding: Limp cover in heavy coated and textured paper, surface-dyed a pale yellow and embossed with pattern of plumes, scrolls, and floral motifs ; sewn in spring green and dark blue thread, six stations, through paper cover ; overall in fair condition with staining and abrasion ; housed in envelope.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Origin: Pertains to the Jalālī year 1235 [1856-1857] suggesting a date of transcription around this time ; watermarks consistent with such a dating. Illuminated heading on opening horiscope suggests transcription in Istanbul.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="561" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Inscription in pencil on interior of upper cover "Probably a horoscope | Turkish with Arabic titles | Triangular signs, etc." ; inscribed by the Library on p.3 "Tracy McGregor Gift" ; annotations clarify observations and elucidate the meanings of symbols employed.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="541" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Purchased in Cairo, 1933/34.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="538" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Mode of access: Internet.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="510" ind1="4" ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Hofelich, M. and D.M. title_top: Every man his own gardener. Being a new, and much more complete gardener's kalendar, and general director, than any one hitherto published. Containing ... an account of what work is necessary to be done in the kitchen and fruit garden, pleasure ground, flower garden and shrubbery; nursery, green-house, and hot-house for every month in the year ... With complete practical directions for forcing all kinds of choice plants ... also particular directions relative to soil and situation ... And to the whole are added, complete and useful lists of kitchen garden plants, fruit trees, forest trees, flowering shrubs ... proper for cultivation in the English gardens and plantations ... And, to which in this edition, are added, additional systematic general catalogues of hardy herbaceous perennials and biennials, and of hot-house plants (not in any former edition) ... By Thomas Mawe ... John Abercrombie ... and other gardeners.

Aldous.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="260" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Washington, D.C. :</subfield><subfield code="b">U.S. Dept. of the Interior, Fish and Wildlife Service :</subfield><subfield code="b">U.S. G.P.O.,</subfield><subfield code="c">1942.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="300" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="a">ii, 56 p. :</subfield><subfield code="b">ill., tables ;</subfield><subfield code="c">23 cm.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="490" ind1="0" ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Research report (U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service) ;</subfield><subfield code="v">5</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Research supported by the United States Department of the Interior, Fish and Wildlife Service.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="504" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Includes bibliographical references (p. 55-56).</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="505" ind1="0" ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Reason for the study.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="505" ind1="0" ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Description.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="505" ind1="0" ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Distribution.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="505" ind1="0" ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Life history notes.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="505" ind1="0" ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Damage caused by ravens.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="505" ind1="0" ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Food habits.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="505" ind1="0" ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Economic status.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="505" ind1="0" ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Crop protection.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="505" ind1="0" ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Literature cited.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="520" ind1="3" ind2=" "><subfield code="a">The white-necked raven (Corvus cryptoleucus), a close relative of the common crow, is indigenous to southwestern United States. Because in parts of its range it has gained the same ill repute as acquired by the crow and magpie in their respective ranges, a 5-year detailed study of its activities and food habits was made, during which many field data were gathered, and the contents of 827 stomachs were analyzed.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="520" ind1="3" ind2=" "><subfield code="a">The omnivorous food habits of this raven often bring it into direct competition with farming interests, and frequently its depredations result in severe damage to crops, particularly to grain sorghums, corn, melons, peanuts, pecans, weak lambs, and poultry. To reduce these attacks and keep the losses at a minimum often is expensive and requires considerable work on the part of ranchers and farmers. On the other hand nearly half the raven's food is of animal origin and includes a wide assortment of insects, many of which are harmful to crops. Grasshoppers, weevils, May beetles, caterpillars, fly maggots, and like pests constitute a material part of the insect diet. Carrion is another important food of the raven, and its removal from the range is a definite aid to sanitation.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="520" ind1="3" ind2=" "><subfield code="a">When heavy raven concentrations occur, the crops must be protected. As effective control is impossible when natural food is abundant, it is generally necessary to resort of frightening measures until winter sets in and the food supply becomes low enough to insure control success. Various contrivances to scare the birds away may be placed in the fields, but the shotgun is without question the best frightening device. The most successful, selective and humane control measure is the use of large cage traps. As the need for control is usually local and varies by seasons, depending upon the crop situation, the soundest policy is to resort of it only when necessary and to take advantage of the bird's better attributes at all other times.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="538" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Mode of access: Internet.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="650" ind1=" " ind2="0"><subfield code="a">Ravens</subfield><subfield code="x">Ecology.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="650" ind1=" " ind2="0"><subfield code="a">Agricultural pests</subfield><subfield code="x">Control.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="650" ind1=" " ind2="0"><subfield code="a">Bird pests.</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="700" ind1="1" ind2=" "><subfield code="a">Lemon, J. series2: Research report (U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service) ;
publisher: U.S. Dept. of the Interior, Fish and Wildlife Service
title: The White-necked raven in relation to agriculture / Shaler E. Aldous.
summary: The white-necked raven (Corvus cryptoleucus), a close relative of the common crow, is indigenous to southwestern United States. Because in parts of its range it has gained the same ill repute as acquired by the crow and magpie in their respective ranges, a 5-year detailed study of its activities and food habits was made, during which many field data were gathered, and the contents of 827 stomachs were analyzed.

The omnivorous food habits of this raven often bring it into direct competition with farming interests, and frequently its depredations result in severe damage to crops, particularly to grain sorghums, corn, melons, peanuts, pecans, weak lambs, and poultry. To reduce these attacks and keep the losses at a minimum often is expensive and requires considerable work on the part of ranchers and farmers. On the other hand nearly half the raven's food is of animal origin and includes a wide assortment of insects, many of which are harmful to crops. Grasshoppers, weevils, May beetles, caterpillars, fly maggots, and like pests constitute a material part of the insect diet. Carrion is another important food of the raven, and its removal from the range is a definite aid to sanitation.

When heavy raven concentrations occur, the crops must be protected. As effective control is impossible when natural food is abundant, it is generally necessary to resort of frightening measures until winter sets in and the food supply becomes low enough to insure control success. Various contrivances to scare the birds away may be placed in the fields, but the shotgun is without question the best frightening device. The most successful, selective and humane control measure is the use of large cage traps. As the need for control is usually local and varies by seasons, depending upon the crop situation, the soundest policy is to resort of it only when necessary and to take advantage of the bird's better attributes at all other times.

Together with the remarkable vision of Lewis XIV; for the interpretation of which he offered a reward of 20,000 louis d'ors, in the Paris Gazette of November 11, 1689 (London : G. Terry, 1795).--No.II. Containing a most extraordinary prophecy, delivered near one hundred years ago, before the Senate,at Frankfort in Germany, concerning the judgments of God on the whole Roman Empire; the Revolutions of, and the calamities that are to happen in, the different nations of the world, especially those of Germany, France, Poland, Holland, &c., by J. M. Daut (1794).</subfield></datafield><datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" "><subfield code="a">[No. III] Prophetical extracts. Containing a very scarce prophetic piece, intitled [sic], A cry from the desart [sic], or, testimonials of the miraculous things lately come to pass in the Cevennes, or Southern parts of France. Verified upon oath, and by other proofs. [by Maximilian Misson] (1794).--No. IV. Prophetical extracts. Relative to the revolution in France, and the decline of the papal power in the world: selected from Fleming, Usher, Jerieu, Goodwin, Gill, Love, Daut, Brown, Knox, Willison, More, Newton, Lacey, Owen, Marion, Cavalier, and many more (1794).--No. V. Prophetical extracts. Relative to the revolution in France...The lives, prophecies, visions, and revelations, of Christopher Kotterus, and Christina Poniatonia, two eminent prophets, in Germany, containing predictions concerning the Pope, the King of France, and the Roman Empire ; with the sudden destruction of the papal power, the miraculous conversion of the Turks, the calling in of the Jews, and the uniting all religions into one universal visible church.
